{
  "text": "Although, RADX is not essential for survival in cells, where knockout has been tested, its absence slows replication forks and leads to DSB formation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . These defects in RADX-deficient cells are rescued by depletion of RAD51, SMA RCAL1, ZRA NB3, and the MUS81 nuclease [CITATION_3] . In light of the data described regarding the role of RAD51 in replication fork reversal, these results suggest that in the absence of RADX, hyperactivity of RAD51 interferes with normal replication and promotes inappropriate replication fork remodeling that results in increased processing by MUS81 [CITATION_4]  Fig. 4 A) .",
  "correct_citation": {
